<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1888-07-25T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1888-07-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="224" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d224">
                    <head>No. 224.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Denby</persName></hi>.</head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1888-07-25"><hi rend="italic">July</hi> 25,
                            1888</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 338.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                        dispatch, No. 646, of May 26 last, in regard to the exclusion of Chinese
                        from Australia.</p>
                    <p>Your dispatch is interesting in its bearing on the general problem of Chinese
                        emigration and the competition of Chinese with domestic labor, which appears
                        to demand an effective solution in other countries besides the United
                        States.</p>
                    <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                    <closer><signed><persName><hi rend="smallcaps">T. F.
                            Bayard.</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>